english:
  title: A Letter Recommending Seo Hae to Minister Lee of the Ministry of Personnel
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: "On this day, we humbly bow a hundred times and present this letter at the gate of the Celestial Ministry's scholar.\n\nConsider a wealthy merchant in his shop. He keeps rare treasures and waits for buyers to come of their own accord. When asked the price, he may demand fifty thousand gold—and still the goods sell. But should that same merchant take his wares door to door, crying out in the streets, \"I wish to sell this!\"—then even at fifty thousand gold, the price begins to waver and fall. The treasure finds no buyer, for now it is the merchant who seeks the sale, not the buyer who seeks the goods. So it is with scholars. Though one possess rare talents and uncommon wisdom, if he lacks the dignity to stand upon his own worth and instead chases eagerly after the approval of the world, his value only diminishes, and still he remains unsold. Such is the nature of things.\n\nNow, coming to your gate with this treasure of fifty thousand gold, crying out for sale, I fear the price may fall and still find no buyer. Therefore, I offer this explanation first, laying bare our humble circumstances before you. We pray you will observe and give us hearing.\n\nAmong our friends, we have found in Seo Hae a scholar of true excellence. His character runs deep and vast, possessed of great capacity. As the ancients said, people may recognize a treasure, yet find no name for the vessel that holds it. Yet to speak in broad terms: he is like the Yellow Bell and Great Pitch—whatever note is struck, it resounds in perfect harmony. This speaks to his mastery of learning and his keen, ready response. He is like a lonely peak, a precipice with thousand-foot walls of stone—speaking to the richness of his writing and the elegant beauty of his compositions. He is like the Three Rivers and Seven Lakes, flowing naturally downward—speaking to the breadth of his judgment, unobstructed and unhindered. He is like autumn frost and blazing sun, awesome and fearsome—speaking to the nobility of his character, which cannot be casually approached. \n\nAmong the scholars of all under Heaven, when one excels in one thing, he often falls short in another. Yet Seo Hae has achieved what few accomplish—excellence in all. Were he appointed to attend the Golden Hall, he would surely possess the elegant refinement of Su Che in polishing imperial words. Were he charged with writing history in the Vast Library, he would surely possess the mastery of Ban Gu in composing a definitive chronicle. Though our bright age abounds with scholars like a forest, should the realm require a great work of letters, I suspect only this one man of Confucius's own land would suffice.\n\nThe ancients said: \"When a scholar's heart and will are perfected yet his name remains unknown, this is the fault of his friends. When his name is known yet the authorities fail to recommend him, this is the fault of the authorities.\" Now, with such a scholar before us, if his merit remains unrecognized, how can we escape this blame?\n\nYou, sir, through upright writing and upright conduct, have gained the trust of the throne and been elevated to the Ministry of Personnel, where you judge and appraise talent. All men of discernment listen with eager ears and watch with longing eyes, awaiting your judgment on whom to employ. This is precisely the time to cast your net far and wide, to overlook no humble person, to seek near without rejecting kinship—thus fulfilling the hopes of worthy scholars and drawing to the throne all those who honor righteousness.\n\nSome say that knowing people truly is difficult even for sages. How can mediocre men like us presume to recognize merit and offer recommendation? Yet if we scrutinize carefully, even sages have their limits. But if we measure by principle, even ordinary people need not err. Our knowledge of Seo Hae comes from what we have witnessed; what we cannot know, we entrust to your wisdom. We humbly ask that you not dismiss our words because we are humble men. Should there be an opening in the Eastern Archives or the Imperial Library, place Seo Hae's name first on the nomination list. Entrust him with responsibility and observe his performance over time. Should he prove unworthy of our words, cast him out and punish us for our reckless advocacy and concealment of truth. Let this serve as a warning to fortune-seekers everywhere. This would hardly dishonor the court's method of selecting talent.\n\nMoreover, Seo Hae does not associate with those unworthy of him, and he has no family connections at court. Therefore, few would speak for him. We are not motivated by the factionalism of our age, where men band together to promote their favorites as virtuous. Rather, we follow the voice of public judgment, fearing only that you might not know his true worth and thus overlook him.\n\nLet the scales of justice determine the true price of this treasure. Let no rare and precious thing wander from door to door, unsold even at fifty thousand gold. We trust in your discernment and bow twice in gratitude."
  footnotes:
    - The 'Celestial Ministry' (天曹) refers to the Ministry of Personnel, which oversaw the selection and advancement of officials in the Chinese imperial bureaucracy.
    - The 'Yellow Bell and Great Pitch' (黃鐘大呂) are the first two notes of the ancient Chinese musical scale, representing harmony and perfect order.
    - Su Che (蘇頲) was a celebrated Tang Dynasty official known for his eloquent memorials and imperial edicts; Ban Gu (班固) was a Han Dynasty historian who compiled the History of the Former Han Dynasty.
    - The 'Three Rivers and Seven Lakes' is a poetic reference to waterways that flow naturally without obstruction, symbolizing unimpeded eloquence and reasoning.
    - The 'Eastern Archives' (東觀) and 'Imperial Library' (翰掖) were prestigious positions in the imperial bureaucracy associated with historical compilation and literary scholarship.
